":"Repps, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Cheam, Surrey, England":"Cheam, Surrey, England","Bastwick, Norfolkshire, England":"Repps, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Widdington, Essex, England":"Widdington, Essex, England"},"en":{"1407–1455":"1407–1455","1403–1455":"1403–1455","1430–1472":"1430–1472","1430–Male":"1430–Deceased","1435–1507":"1435–1507","1385–1455":"1385–1455","1385–1406":"1385–1406","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","after 1406":"after 1406","1410":"1430","1430":"1430","1385":"1385","1472":"1472","1507":"1507","1407":"1407","1429":"1429","1406":"1406","Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England":"Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England","Repps with Bastwick St Sebastian, Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Repps, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","St Sebastian, Bastwick, Norfolk, England":"Repps, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Cheam, Surrey, England":"Cheam, Surrey, England","Bastwick, Norfolkshire, England":"Repps, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Widdington, Essex, England":"Widdington, Essex, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Goodall","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire):","metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>god(e)</i> ‘good’ + <i>ale</i> ‘ale’; perhaps denoting an innkeeper or tan ale taster. An ale taster was a manorial or borough court official appointed to regulate the quality of ale sold by inns and alewives, especially with the duty of preventing the sale of sour or watered-down ale.","alternatively, it may be a habitational name from Gowdall near Snaith, in Yorkshire. This place was named in Old English with <i>golde</i> ‘marigold’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’."],"variants":[{"name":"Godber","meanings":["English (Nottinghamshire and Derbyshire):","most probably a nickname from Middle English <i>god(e)</i>, <i>gud(e)</i> ‘good’ + <i>b(i)er</i> ‘beer’, a metonymic occupational name for a brewer or a nickname for a toper. Compare   Goodall  .","alternatively, perhaps a nickname from medieval catchphrase, either <i>God be her</i> ‘May God be here (i.e. in this house)’ or <i>gōd be her</i> ‘may good be here’. Such phrasal names were common in England in the Middle Ages, although most have now died out."]},{"name":"Goodale","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Goodall  ."]},{"name":"Goodell","meanings":["English (Hampshire and Surrey): variant of   Goodall  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Goodale","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (London and East Anglia): variant of   Goodall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Goodall","meanings":["English (mainly Yorkshire and Nottinghamshire):","metonymic occupational name from Middle English <i>god(e)</i> ‘good’ + <i>ale</i> ‘ale’; perhaps denoting an innkeeper or tan ale taster. An ale taster was a manorial or borough court official appointed to regulate the quality of ale sold by inns and alewives, especially with the duty of preventing the sale of sour or watered-down ale.","alternatively, it may be a habitational name from Gowdall near Snaith, in Yorkshire. This place was named in Old English with <i>golde</i> ‘marigold’ + <i>halh</i> ‘nook, recess’."]}]},{"name":"Frances","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Feminine form of   Francis .  In the 16th century the two spellings were used indiscriminately for both sexes, the distinction in spelling not being established until the 17th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Beckwith","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Yorkshire named Beckwith, from Old English <i>bēce</i> ‘beech’ + Old Norse <i>vithr</i> ‘wood’ (replacing the cognate Old English <i>wudu</i>).","History: Most if not all present-day bearers of the surname are probably descended from William Beckwith who held the manor of Beckwith in 1364."],"variants":[{"name":"Beckworth","meanings":["English: variant of   Beckwith  ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":48,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Frances Beckwith Goodall Goodale was born in 1407, in Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England, her father, Lord Goodall Goodale, was 22 and her mother, Sarah Squier, was 23. She married Sir Thomas William de Marston in 1429, in Repps, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1455, in Norfolk, England, at the age of 48."},"et":{"1407–1455":"1407–1455","1403–1455":"1403–1455","1430–1472":"1430–1472","1430–Male":"1430–Surnud","1435–1507":"1435–1507","1385–1455":"1385–1455","1385–1406":"1385–1406","1403":"1403","1435":"1435","1455":"1455","after 1406":"pärast 1406","1410":"1430","1430":"1430","1385":"1385","1472":"1472","1507":"1507","1407":"1407","1429":"1429","1406":"1406","Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England":"Repps with Bastwick, Norfolk, England","Repps with Bastwick St Sebastian, Great Yarmouth, Norfolk, England":"Repps, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","St Sebastian, Bastwick, Norfolk, England":"Repps, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Norfolk, England":"Norfolk, England","Cheam, Surrey, England":"Cheam, Surrey, England","Bastwick, 